Homework Assignments (Weekly, 13 total)
Each HW is designed so AI can help but can't yet do it for you — the deliverables are machine-specific traces, patches that must actually compile, or measurements from the student's own environment.
HW1 (Week 1) — Browser Forensics. Using only chrome:// internal pages, produce a one-page report documenting: (a) your exact Chromium/Chrome version and V8 version, (b) three active field trials on your machine, (c) the list of registered URL schemes, (d) one flag in chrome://flags you'd enable and why. Screenshots required. AI-resistant because: values are unique to each student's install.
HW2 (Week 2) — The Build. Complete a full Chromium build from source. Deliverable: a screenshot of your custom-built content_shell or chrome window with the page title showing your unityID, and the output of autoninja -C out/Default chrome -d explain for the final link step, and total wall-clock build time. (Lab machines available for students without 100GB free.) AI-resistant: you cannot fake a build.
HW3 (Week 3) — Code Archaeology. Pick any feature from this list — window.alert, document.title, navigator.userAgent, console.log, <input type="color">. Using Chromium Code Search, trace the full path from the JS call to the underlying platform implementation. Produce a diagram with file paths and line numbers for at least 5 hops (IDL → Blink binding → Blink implementation → Mojo interface → browser-process handler). AI-resistant: requires navigating the real tree; AI hallucinates file paths here constantly.
HW4 (Week 4) — Parser Pathology. Write 5 HTML snippets that produce surprising DOM trees (e.g., <p><div></div></p>, unclosed tags inside tables, </br> vs <br/>). For each: (a) predict the DOM, (b) verify with document.body.outerHTML, (c) cite the relevant step in the HTML spec's tokenizer/tree-construction algorithm. AI-resistant: the surprising cases require hands-on verification.
HW5 (Week 5) — Style Profiling. Build a page with ≥1000 DOM nodes. Cause (a) a style recalc affecting few nodes, (b) a style recalc affecting all nodes, (c) a recalc that's surprisingly expensive. Capture Performance panel traces for all three and explain the cost difference. AI-resistant: requires real traces from real hardware.
HW6 (Week 6) — Layout Thrashing. Write JS that causes forced synchronous layout ("layout thrashing") in a loop, measure its cost, then refactor to batch reads and writes. Report FPS before/after with traces. AI-resistant: measurements are machine-specific.
Midterm 1 week — no new HW.
HW7 (Week 7) — V8 Under the Microscope. Install d8 (from your Chromium build — it's already there in out/Default/d8). For a function you write, produce: (a) its bytecode via --print-bytecode, (b) its optimized code via --print-opt-code after warming it up, (c) a triggered deopt with --trace-deopt and a plausible explanation of why it deopted. AI-resistant: outputs are version-specific and verbose; can't be plausibly faked.
HW8 (Week 8) — Embedding V8, Sort Of. Modify the V8 "hello world" embedder example to: (a) run JS that reads input from C++, (b) expose a C++ function to JS, (c) handle an uncaught exception gracefully. Submit your .cc file and a terminal recording (asciinema or screen recording) of it running. AI-resistant: has to actually link and run.
HW9 (Week 9) — Process Zoo. Open a specific set of tabs (provided), open the Chrome Task Manager, and explain why each process exists, what site it's associated with, and which are sandboxed. Induce an OOPIF (out-of-process iframe) and prove it via Task Manager. AI-resistant: requires hands-on observation.
HW10 (Week 10) — Read a .mojom. Pick one .mojom file in the tree (list provided). Produce: (a) English-language interface description, (b) the client-side call site with file+line, (c) the server-side handler, (d) a diagram of the message flow. AI-resistant: AI hallucinates on specific mojom files.
HW11 (Week 11) — Netlog Safari. Capture a chrome://net-export log while loading a specific page (provided). Using Netlog Viewer, answer: number of DNS queries, number of TCP connections vs. reused, which requests went over HTTP/3, total bytes, longest-blocking resource. AI-resistant: netlog is unique per capture.
Midterm 2 week — no new HW.
HW12 (Week 12) — Molecular Viewer in WebGPU. Starter code provided (basic WebGPU triangle). Extend it to render a set of atoms (PDB file provided) as shaded spheres using instanced rendering. Bonus: implement ambient occlusion via a compute shader. AI-resistant: WebGPU API is recent enough that AI often writes broken code; students must debug.
HW13 (Week 13) — Device API OR PWA. Pick one:

Build a web app that connects to a real (or emulated) USB/Bluetooth/Serial device and reads data.
Build a PWA that works fully offline, stores data in IndexedDB, and syncs via Background Sync when online.
